Know how to set up a repository; 

 1) git init; 
 2) git clone; 
 3) git config;

Know how to save changes: 

 1) git add; 
 2) git commit; 
 3) .gitignore;

Know how to sync a repository: 

 1) git remote; 
 2) git fetch; 
 3) git push; 
 4) git pull;

Know how to save changes: 

 1) git diff; 
 2) git stash;

Know how to inspect a repository: 

 1) git tag; 
 2) git blame;

Know how to undo changes: 

 1) git clean; 
 2) git revert; 
 3) git reset; 
 4) git rm;

Know how to rewrite history: 

 1) git commit --amend; 
 2) git reflog;

Know how to use branches: 

 1) git branch; 
 2) git checkout; 
 3) git merge; 
 4) Merge conflicts;

Know the basic configuration file aspects: 

 1) Config levels: 
 2) core.editor; 
 3) merge.tool; 
 4) color.ui, color*; 
 5) remote; 
 6) user; 
 7) pull / push; 
 8) merge / mergetool, diff / difftool; 
 9) log; 
 10) http; 
 11) format; 
 12) credential; 
 13) commit;

Know how to rewrite history: 

 1) git rebase; 
 2) git rebase -i;

Advanced logging: 

 1) Formatting log output; 
 2) Git Filtering the commit history;

Refs and the Reflog: 

 1) Hashes; 
 2) Refs; 
 3) Packed / Special refs; 
 4) Refspecs; 
 5) Relative Refs: ~ vs ^; 
 6) The reflog;

Know the branching strategies, know the GitFlow: 

 1) Centralized workflow; 
 2) Feature branch workflow; 
 3) Gitflow workflow; 
 4) Forking workflow;

Know the conditions syntax; 

 1) If .. else 
 2) Switch / break / default

Understand what is eval, how it works and what are the pitfalls and risks it can cause; 

 1) Know the difference between direct and indirect eval calls; 
 2) Know the safer and faster alternative: new Function;

Know how to perform CRUD operations: 

 1) Create new Entries; 
 2) Read entities; 
 3) Update entries; 
 4) Update individual properties; 
 5) Delete entries;
